-- Prelude
Immediately after checking out this repository, type this command: 'source link.sh'
to link important files from ../decNumber  and ../IntelRDFPMathLib1.0 that are 
necessary for compilation.  (Note, this is done for you by using ../make_benchmarks.sh)

-- Introduction
This is the Euro Conversion benchmark, part of the decimal floating-point benchmark suite. This
benchmarks performs conversions between currencies using the Euro as an intermediate currency.
For details, please check the paper Wang et al. "Benchmarks and Performance Analysis of Decimal 
Floating-Point Applications" from IEEE International Conference on Computer Design, Oct 2007. 

To run this benchmark using the decNumber library, you need to have your decNumber 
library setup correctly and have the libraries, LINUXDecFloats.a or LINUXDecNum.a, generated.

To run this benchmark using the Intel Decimal Floating-Point Math library, you will
need to have this library set up correctly and have the library libbid.a generated.

To run this benchmark using native gcc BID types, you must have at least gcc4.3 
installed with decimal floating-point types enabled. For instructions on this 
please refer to http://gcc.gnu.org/. You will also need to link dfp-round.h,
which is located in the nativeGccLib directory.

Please refer to the README file in the decNumber, IntelRDFPMathLib10U1, and 
nativeGccLib directories for more details on using the dfp libraries.

Also provide symbolic link to all *.c and *.h files of the decNumber
library if you want to use this with Intel VTune or gprof.  A script, link.sh
is provided to help with this task.

Please refer to the testGen directory to find out how to generate directed pseudo-random 
tests to be used in this benchmark

-- Macro definition:
TEST_INPUT = input file name
DEC_DATATYPE = [DECNUMBER_ARBITRARY|DECNUMBER_FIXED|BID|NATIVE_GCC_BID]
BITWIDTH = [64|128]

-- Test Generation
Small sample input files are provided, as well as a test generation program to create
arbitrarily large pseudo-random input data. See the README file in the testGen directory

-- Compilation
To compile this benchmark, there are several options you can use
1) To compile this benchmark in Linux to print no debugging information:
	make clean; make OS=LINUX
2) To compile this benchmark in Linux to print debugging information (-g) 
	make clean; make OS=LINUX DEBUG=-g
3) To compile this benchmark in Linux to print debugging information (-g) and 
   verbose output :
	make clean; make OS=LINUX DEBUG="-g -D DEBUG"
4) To compile this benchmark using a specific dfp library:
	make clean; 
	make OS=LINUX DEC_DATATYPE=[DECNUMBER_ARBITRARY|DECNUMBER_FIXED|BID|NATIVE_GCC_BID] WIDTH=[BITWIDTH]
5) To compile this benchmark with PROFILING information, first, you need to create symbolic link for
   all files in the decNumber library in this directory. The default files you see in this 
   directory links to the old decNumber library, not the latest decFloat library

-- Execution
To execute this program, run
	`Euro.LINUX.$DEC_DATATYPE $TEST_INPUT'

-- SimpleScalar
To run this benchmark with SimpleScalar and evaluate the decNumber library
	make clean; make OS=SW
1) Once you are done (4)
	(e) run with `./sim-outorder Euro.SW.DECNUMBER_ARBITRARY $TEST_INPUT
	    $TEST_OUTPUT >& sim.report'
	(f) Run `perl ../parse_sim_outorder_output.pl sim.report 1' to convert SimpleScalar 
	    report to a format that can be processed by Excel (space delimited). It generates
            three outputs, sim.respot_dec.txt gives statistics about decimal function,
 	    sim.report_sig.txt shows the number of multiplier digits for all decimal multiplication
            in this benchmark run, sim.report.txt convert typical simplescalar output to a 
            Excel friendly format.
6) To run this benchmark with SimpleScalar and evaluate the decimal hardware
   instructions
	make clean; make OS=HW
	run with `./sim-outorder Euro.HW.DECNUMBER_ARBITRARY 100k_test.in
        100k_test.out >& sim.report'
	Run `perl decOperation.pl sim.report' to convert SimpleScalar 
	report to *.csv format
7) For 4) and 5), you can also add DEBUG="-D DEBUG" if you want verbose output
